  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1269672/files/A-Abar-combined.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00000 Universality of coefficients $\bar{A}_{n,\ell}$ (left) and $A_{n,\ell}$ (right) with polytropic index $n$. Top panels give the coefficients themselves, while the bottom panels show the relative fractional difference between the coefficients and the averaged value over $n\in [0.3,1]$. The fractional variation in $A_{n,0}$ (the $M_{2}$--$S_{1}$ relation) is less than 0.5\% over this range. Even up to $\ell=4$ (which controls the $M_{10}$--$S_{9}$ relation), there is less than 5\% variation.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1269672/files/comparison-with-pappas.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00001 (Color online) Comparison between relativistic and Newtonian three-hair relations. Top: Newtonian (solid red, this work), and relativistic (dashed blue, from~\cite{Pappas:2013naa}) $\bar{S}_3$ vs. $\bar{M}_2$ relation for an $n=1$ polytrope and arbitrary spin frequency. The parameter along both curves is stellar compactness. Bottom: Fractional difference between the relativistic and Newtonian results.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1269672/files/growing-degeneracy.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00002 Schematic breakdown of universality at high $\ell$. A solution for $\bar{M}_{2\ell+2},\bar{S}_{2\ell+1}$ comes from the intersection of a straight line (Equation~\eqref{eq:1st-no-hair}; here plotted with $\bar{M}_{2}=3$) with a power law [Equation~\eqref{eq:2nd-no-hair}]. The width of the power law comes from the EoS dependence of the prefactor $\bar{A}_{n,\ell}$. At high $\ell$, the power law approaches linearity and the universality degenerates, as the intersection region grows.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1269672/files/arXiv:1312.4532.pdf</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1269672/files/Newtonian-S3Q-for-3hair-PAonly.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00001 Comparison between relativistic and weak-field three-hair relations. Top: weak-field (solid blue, this work), and relativistic $\bar{S}_3$ vs.~$\bar{M}_2$ relation for an $n=0.5$ polytrope (blue dashed) and the fit among realistic EoSs (red dot-dashed) from~\citet{Pappas:2013naa}. The parameter along all curves is stellar compactness. Bottom: fractional difference between the relativistic and our weak-field results.</subfield>
  </datafield>
